  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhanced Health Service Delivery with the Haitian Red Cross</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As Haiti strives to extend health services delivery and improve health outcomes by providing the population with equitable access to primary health services, the MSPP has launched an initiative that revolves around community-based interventions. One key element of the MSPP&#x2019;s strategy is to increase the availability of professional health resources by training and deploying 10,000 &#x201C;Agents de Sant&#xE9; Communautaires Polyvalents&#x201D; or ASCPs. The Haitian Red Cross as a long term partner to MSPP seeks to improve the effectiveness and efficiency of the services expected from the ASCP initiative and to build health resilience capacity at the community levels by leveraging its country-wide network of volunteers

The goal of the project is to contribute to building resilience in targeted communities in Haiti through improved access to primary health services and availability of trained personnel.

The project is divided into two pillars responsive to each objective. 

Pillar 1 will contribute to improving access to primary health services in Haiti by training and mobilizing HRC Health Volunteers to conduct health education and promotion in the community; and training &#x201C;Agent de Sant&#xE9; Communautaires Polyvalents&#x201D; and supporting MSPP in their deployment to serve as resources for primary health care at the community level. Under this pilar, 40 ASCPs will be trained, deployed and supported by 320 ASCPs at an average ratio of 1:8 of ASCP to HRCV-H.

Pillar 2 will support HRC to strengthen the training service capacity by improving their training infrastructure and obtaining national recognition as a training provider, which will result in a source of revenue for HRC.</narrative>
  </description>
